div.p:
“One has no right to judge from appearance,” said Mr. Hadley. “Facts are the sole
                    standard, and this Will is dated subsequently to that in favour of Mrs. Crump;
                    therefore it stands good rather than that.”

“Whatever some people do of right is noised abroad, and carried to their credit;
                    and let others do whatever they will it soaks in, and nobody thinks anything of
                    it.”

“Be it so,” said Robert, after a pause. “That paper might have borne the dearest
                    name in the world; and at this moment I should have been at the end of trouble;
                    joy in place of sorrow would have been mine. As it is, sorrow has settled down;
                    it is a tangible presence. Be it so.”
